57
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:45,203
<i>and ours takes us to the year 1867.</i>

58
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:49,164
<i>An army that had fought
in the war between the states,</i>

59
00:06:49,280 --> 00:06:53,365
<i>that had bravely battled
in many an Indian campaign,</i>

60
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:56,529
<i>now patrolled the West in a time of peace,</i>

61
00:06:56,640 --> 00:06:59,211
<i>with ever-present thoughts of home.</i>

62
00:06:59,960 --> 00:07:01,928
<i>The Indian was back on the reservation,</i>

63
00:07:02,040 --> 00:07:06,841
<i>where the Peace Commission of 1867
had met with various warlike tribes</i>

64
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:09,691
<i>and secured certain promises from them.</i>

65
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:12,690
<i>In return, papers were given to Indians,</i>

66
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:18,045
<i>certifying them to be good citizens
who would obey the laws of the land.</i>

67
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:20,447
<i>Many gifts were distributed.</i>

68
00:07:21,480 --> 00:07:23,847
<i>Beads,</i>

69
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:32,047
<i>pieces of cloth,</i>

70
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:35,962
<i>ammunition,</i>

71
00:07:36,720 --> 00:07:39,087
<i>and war-surplus rifles.</i>

72
00:07:46,160 --> 00:07:50,643
<i>Naturally, these rifles</i> were
<i>quite unfamiliar to the Indians.</i>

73
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:57,089
<i>Of course, it was understood
these weapons were to be used</i>

74
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:59,771
<i>solely for the purpose of hunting game.</i>

75
00:08:02,360 --> 00:08:04,966
<i>The leaves fumed early in that year.</i>

76
00:08:05,960 --> 00:08:08,122
<i>It could be a long, hard winter.</i>

77
00:08:08,920 --> 00:08:11,127
<i>The signs were everywhere.</i>

78
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:16,406
<i>In the high country, the morning frost
would sometimes last until afternoon.</i>

79
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:18,648
<i>Buffalo were feeding ravenously.</i>

80
00:08:18,760 --> 00:08:22,685
<i>Beaver were damming
and storing with strange vigour.</i>

81
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:27,124
<i>Horses and dogs were becoming
shaggy-haired as never before.</i>

82
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:32,048
<i>And it could be sensed in the booming,
bustling mining town of Denver.</i>

83
00:08:32,840 --> 00:08:37,607
<i>Most historians agree that the events
leading to the Battle of Whiskey Hills</i>

84
00:08:37,720 --> 00:08:40,326
<i>and the subsequent disaster
at Quicksand Bottoms</i>

85
00:08:40,440 --> 00:08:43,683
<i>began here in Denver,
at a miners' meeting.</i>

86
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:49,841
<i>Such meetings were frequent and held
as part of the political fabric of the town.</i>

87
00:08:50,800 --> 00:08:54,964
<i>But the meeting of November 4th
had a marked air of grim foreboding.</i>

88
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:59,240
