00:18:38,040 --> 00:18:42,807
Ladies, you have heard it said
that man is all mouth and muscle,

225
00:18:42,920 --> 00:18:46,970
that he is dirty boots on one end
and a dirty mind on the other.

226
00:18:47,080 --> 00:18:48,650
Don't you believe it.

227
00:18:48,760 --> 00:18:52,526
If we are to enjoy equal rights with man,
we must respect him,

228
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:56,850
and, if we are to respect him,
then we must save him from himself

229
00:18:56,960 --> 00:19:00,123
and from the poison of alcoholic spirits!

230
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:02,846
- Do you agree?
- Yes!

231
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:04,928
Then let the world know it.

232
00:19:05,040 --> 00:19:09,728
Let us spread the word of emancipation
to every comer of this great nation.

233
00:19:10,840 --> 00:19:13,525
Emancipation! Let me hear it!

234
00:19:13,640 --> 00:19:15,961
Emancipation!

235
00:19:16,080 --> 00:19:19,801
- Freedom for women!
- Freedom for women!

236
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:24,164
Shout it out, ladies!
Women can remake the world!

237
00:19:24,280 --> 00:19:27,204
Women can remake the world!

238
00:19:29,560 --> 00:19:33,007
♪ Mine eyes have seen the glory
of the coming of the Lord

239
00:19:33,120 --> 00:19:36,727
♪ He is trampling out the vintage
where the grapes of wrath are stored

240
00:19:36,840 --> 00:19:40,526
♪ He hath loosed the fateful lightning
of his terrible swift sword

241
00:19:40,640 --> 00:19:44,531
♪ His truth is marching on

242
00:19:45,040 --> 00:19:48,442
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

243
00:19:48,840 --> 00:19:52,242
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

244
00:19:52,680 --> 00:19:55,843
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

245
00:19:55,960 --> 00:19:59,806
♪ His truth is marching on

246
00:20:00,440 --> 00:20:03,046
Ladies! Let me hear it!

247
00:20:03,160 --> 00:20:05,527
Emancipation!

248
00:20:05,640 --> 00:20:09,725
- Shout it out!
- Freedom for women!

249
00:20:10,040 --> 00:20:14,841
- Once again!
- Women can remake the world!

250
00:20:16,160 --> 00:20:18,128
<i>(women screaming)</i>

251
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:27,044
What do you think, Sergeant?

252
00:20:27,160 --> 00:20:31,563
I hate to say it, Colonel, but it sounds like
Sioux or Cheyenne war cries to me, sir.

253
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:33,648
An uprising at the fort?

254
00:20:34,360 --> 00:20:36,522
- Ridiculous.
- Yes, sir.

255
00:20:39,400 --> 00:20:43,200
♪ I can read his righteous sentence
by the dim and flaring lamps

256
00:20:43,320 --> 00:20:47,450
♪ His truth is marching on

257
00:20:49,680 --> 00:20:51,842
Those are bugles, sir.

258
00:20:54,320 --> 00:20:57,722
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

259
00:20:58,160 --> 00:21:01,482
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

260
00:21:01,960 --> 00:21:05,123
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

261
00:21:05,240 --> 00:21:09,040
♪ His truth is marching on

262
00:21:19,280 --> 00:21:22,966
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

263
00:21:23,240 --> 00:21:26,369
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

264
00:21:26,960 --> 00:21:30,123
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

265
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:34,007
♪ His truth is marching on

266
00:21:35,680 --> 00:21:37,648
That's cannon, sir!

267
00:21:37,760 --> 00:21:42,129
- Form a skirmish line to the left!
- Form a skirmish line to the left! Ho!

268
00:21:48,480 --> 00:21:52,405
♪ In the beauty of the lilies
Christ was born across the sea

269
00:21:52,520 --> 00:21:56,161
♪ With a glory in his bosom
that transfigures you and me

270
00:21:56,400 --> 00:21:58,562
Draw carbines! Ho!

271
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:03,807
Company B returning. Open the gates.

272
00:22:05,320 --> 00:22:06,685
♪ Glory, glory...

273
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:09,610
- My God! She's on fire, sir!
- Charge!

274
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:16,123
♪ Glory, glory, hallelujah

275
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:18,208
♪ His truth is...

276
00:22:32,040 --> 00:22:34,930
- You!
- Good evening, Colonel.

277
00:22:35,880 --> 00:22:38,042
Bandmaster, front and centre.

278
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:44,121
You're under arrest.
This entire band is under arrest.

279
00:22:44,240 --> 00:22:47,005
You're confined to quarters
until further notice.

280
00:22:47,120 --> 00:22:49,088
Dismissed!

281
00:22:50,840 --> 00:22:52,968
Who are the idiots
who fired those cannon?

282
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:55,560
- Sergeant Perkins.
- Private McIntosh.

283
00:22:55,680 --> 00:22:58,331
- Private Johnson.
- Private Williams.

284
00:22:58,440 --> 00:23:01,125
Report to my quarters
tomorrow morning at nine.

285
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:02,446
Yes, sir.

286
00:23:02,560 --> 00:23:04,483
Brady.

287
00:23:04,600 --> 00:23:08,446
Return carbines.
In file, prepare to dismount.

288
00:23:08,560 --> 00:23:10,528
Dismount.

289
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:16,369
Madam. Article twelve, section seven,
paragraph two of army regulations

290
00:23:16,480 --> 00:23:20,929
states: "Government property cannot
be used for political demonstrations."

291
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:24,203
Sir, we have never designated
our movement to be political.

292
00:23:24,320 --> 00:23:28,405
Article nine, section two, paragraph four
of army regulations clearly states

293
00:23:28,520 --> 00:23:31,603
that civilian meetings may be held
at military installations

294
00:23:31,720 --> 00:23:34,803
when permission has been granted
by the commanding officer.

295
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:38,049
The commanding officer? I see.

296
00:23:38,880 --> 00:23:42,680
Forgive me, madam. We've been on patrol
for six days. I'm somewhat weary.

297
00:23:42,800 --> 00:23:45,087
Captain Slater gave you
permission in my absence?

298
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:47,168
He did.

299
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:55,531
- Brady, I want this mess cleaned up.
- Yes, sir.

300
00:23:55,640 --> 00:23:59,167
Ladies, I see you have transport.
You'll be escorted back to town.

301
00:23:59,280 --> 00:24:02,489
The party will leave
in five minutes exactly.

302
00:24:03,200 --> 00:24:06,170
- Madam, do you have quarters here?
- I have.

303
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:09,970
Then you may retire
to those quarters, madam,

304
00:24:10,080 --> 00:24:14,085
and remake the world on some
other occasion. Good evening.

305
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:16,362
- Buell.
- Sir!

306
00:24:28,360 --> 00:24:31,523
- Buell, get me Captain Slater.
- Yes, sir.

307
00:25:24,480 --> 00:25:28,201
Excuse me, sir.
Did the colonel wish to see me?

308
00:25:28,320 --> 00:25:32,166
- Where the hell did you come from?
- I couldn't help but overhear, sir.

309
00:25:32,280 --> 00:25:36,251
I want the colonel to know that what
happened tonight, the way it happened,

310
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:39,045
was so quick that I hardly
had time to marshal my forces.

311
00:25:39,160 --> 00:25:42,323
Did you give that woman permission
for a temperance rally?

312
00:25:42,440 --> 00:25:46,286
Yes and no. That is, I had no idea
it would get outta hand, so to speak, sir.

313
00:25:46,400 --> 00:25:48,641
What the hell did you expect?

314
00:25:48,760 --> 00:25:51,764
Give a woman an acorn
and you're up to your rump in oak trees.

315
00:25:51,880 --> 00:25:54,963
That's very true, sir. And I am sorry.

316
00:25:55,080 --> 00:25:58,448
If only they hadn't started moving...
that is to say, marching.

317
00:25:58,560 --> 00:26:02,121
- Led by the Fort Russell band.
- I'd say that Mrs Massingale led them.

318
00:26:02,240 --> 00:26:06,802
The band came next. You see, they were
playing The <i>Battle</i> Hymn of the Republic,

319
00:26:06,920 --> 00:26:10,481
and every time they got to
"Hallelujah" - boom!

320
00:26:11,400 --> 00:26:15,530
- I'm sorry, sir, about the cannon.
- Spare me the details.

321
00:26:15,640 --> 00:26:17,608
Slater, what if word got out

322
00:26:17,720 --> 00:26:20,610
that Fort Russell stood behind
a temperance movement?

323
00:26:20,720 --> 00:26:24,930
That I, a line officer,
could ever support such a movement?

324
00:26:25,040 --> 00:26:27,202
Well, you got a point there, sir.

325
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:32,043
- And you let them go right ahead.
- Well, I, uh...

326
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:36,085
Actually, I was trying to keep the colonel's
daughter out of it, for your sake.

327
00:26:36,200 --> 00:26:38,362
What's my daughter got to do with this?

328
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:40,926
- Well, your daughter...
- Please.

329
00:26:41,040 --> 00:26:43,725
I beg you not to hold
Paul responsible, Father.

330
00:26:43,840 --> 00:26:45,808
It was my fault. I was the one who...

331
00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:49,811
She was not. And I refuse to allow her
to accept responsibility. I was the one.

332
00:26:49,920 --> 00:26:51,604
- You were not.
- Yes, I was.

333
00:26:51,720 --> 00:26:52,881
Paul...

334
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:56,891
- In my own quarters.
- We're sorry, Father, truly we are.

335
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:58,889
- B-but...
- But what?

336
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:00,968
But...

337
00:27:01,680 --> 00:27:06,049
But may I point out, sir, that you have
the only private quarters at the fort,

338
00:27:06,160 --> 00:27:09,050
and we didn't expect you back so soon.

339
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:12,050
It's true that Miss Gearhart
has her own quarters, sir,

340
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:16,927
but I thought that my presence there
might put her in a compromising position.

341
00:27:17,040 --> 00:27:20,283
- Since my own quarters are shared, sir...
- Slater! Answer me.

342
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:23,768
- I'm trying to, sir.
- He isn't either, not truthfully.

343
00:27:23,880 --> 00:27:27,282
He wasn't keeping me out of the
temperance meeting, I was keeping him.

344
00:27:27,400 --> 00:27:30,927
I thought he might try to stop
the marching, so this seemed a lovely...

345
00:27:31,040 --> 00:27:34,249
I mean, a way... to divert him.

346
00:27:34,920 --> 00:27:37,048
Louise.

347
00:27:37,160 --> 00:27:39,561
You don't really mind, do you, darling?

348
00:27:39,680 --> 00:27:43,605
I mean, you certainly couldn't have
enjoyed yourself any the less.

349
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:45,688
Louise!

350
00:27:48,760 --> 00:27:52,003
Well, I'd do anything for
Cora Massingale and her cause.

351
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:56,045
And if you've hurt her, Father,
I'll never forgive you.

352
00:28:09,400 --> 00:28:11,402
- Slater.
- Yes, sir.

353
00:28:11,520 --> 00:28:15,844
The women, the rally, the cannon.
I'll chalk it all up to your inexperience.

354
00:28:15,960 --> 00:28:16,927
Thank you, sir.

355
00:28:17,040 --> 00:28:22,206
But you cannot... you simply cannot use
my quarters for... for this sort of thing.

356
00:28:22,320 --> 00:28:23,651
I'm sorry, sir.

357
00:28:23,760 --> 00:28:27,810
Why don't you just get on with it and
marry the girl? Stop all this lying around?

358
00:28:27,920 --> 00:28:32,244
Well, the colonel knows my feelings about
that, sir. The West is no life for a woman.

359
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:35,728
The West is no life for anyone.
Wind, dust, Indians.

360
00:28:36,920 --> 00:28:40,208
I hate the wind. I hate the dust.
And I hate the Indians.

361
00:28:40,320 --> 00:28:44,609
Yes, I know. And until my transfer
comes through to an eastern post, I'll...

362
00:28:46,160 --> 00:28:48,527
I'll drink to that.

363
00:28:48,640 --> 00:28:52,008
To you and Louise and a transfer.
There you are.

364
00:28:53,160 --> 00:28:55,970
- I can't, sir.
- Why not?

365
00:28:56,080 --> 00:28:59,402
I haven't said good night to Louise yet.
The liquor on my breath...

366
00:28:59,520 --> 00:29:03,002
- She knows you drink, she knows I drink.
- I know that, sir, but...

367
00:29:03,120 --> 00:29:06,886
if you had seen her at that meeting
tonight. She heard Mrs Massingale.

368
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:10,766
Her eyes all lit up.
Frightened hell out of me, sir.

369
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:13,326
All right. Go to her.
Do whatever it is you do.

370
00:29:13,440 --> 00:29:15,807
- Thank you, sir.
- But not on my bear rug!

371
00:29:15,920 --> 00:29:17,888
No. No, sir.

372
00:29:19,680 --> 00:29:22,047
Slater.

373
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:26,290
Here. Escort for a wagon train.
Fella named Wallingham.

374
00:29:26,400 --> 00:29:28,482
Taxpayer, good Republican.

375
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:32,844
I want you to figure out how to intercept
the train and escort them to Denver.

376
00:29:32,960 --> 00:29:36,726
Denver? That'll take over a week.
I promised Louise...

377
00:29:36,840 --> 00:29:39,002
I know, I know. She'll cry, of course.

378
00:29:39,120 --> 00:29:41,646
Just tell her duty is a cruel master.

379
00:29:44,120 --> 00:29:49,206
Yes, sir. Duty... is a cruel... master.

380
00:29:49,320 --> 00:29:51,971
Yes, sir. Thank you. Good night, sir.

381
00:29:58,840 --> 00:30:01,081
- (knocking)
- Colonel Gearhart?

382
00:30:04,880 --> 00:30:06,848
Colonel?

383
00:30:13,440 --> 00:30:15,408
Colonel?

384
00:30:20,520 --> 00:30:21,851
I, uh...

385
00:30:21,960 --> 00:30:26,284
I don't wish to intrude on your privacy,
Colonel, but... this is vitally important.

386
00:30:26,400 --> 00:30:28,607
I'm taking a bath.

387
00:30:28,720 --> 00:30:30,768
The sight of a gentleman taking his bath

388
00:30:30,880 --> 00:30:34,521
is not foreign to a woman
who's been widowed twice.

389
00:30:34,640 --> 00:30:37,883
Well... Would you care to have a seat?

390
00:30:40,760 --> 00:30:44,845
No, thank you. What I have to say
is best said standing.

391
00:30:46,960 --> 00:30:49,281
You'll forgive me if I don't get up.

392
00:30:49,400 --> 00:30:51,562
It's not necessary.

393
00:30:53,600 --> 00:30:59,403
Mrs Massingale, I've already told Captain
Slater I won't hold him responsible.

394
00:30:59,520 --> 00:31:02,649
In your case, I've written off
the entire incident. So now...

395
00:31:02,760 --> 00:31:04,524
That's not why I'm here.

396
00:31:04,640 --> 00:31:08,281
I have received a telegram from Julesburg
that distresses me deeply.

397
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:11,847
It says a train of 40 wagons left there
yesterday bound for Denver

398
00:31:11,960 --> 00:31:15,123
and that you are to furnish
military escort for that train.

399
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:17,607
Is that information correct?

400
00:31:17,720 --> 00:31:20,929
I received a request to that effect, yes.

401
00:31:21,040 --> 00:31:26,251
Were you aware, Colonel, that the cargo
of those 40 wagons is alcohol?

402
00:31:28,760 --> 00:31:31,843
- No, ma'am.
- Well, now you know.

403
00:31:31,960 --> 00:31:34,770
Tell me, Colonel, are you
going to furnish escort?

404
00:31:34,880 --> 00:31:36,644
Yes, ma'am.

405
00:31:37,840 --> 00:31:40,844
I respectfully request
that you reconsider, Colonel.

406
00:31:40,960 --> 00:31:44,601
In the name of suffering humanity,
I implore you to halt that wagon train

407
00:31:44,720 --> 00:31:48,088
and destroy this poison
that they're carrying.

408
00:31:50,120 --> 00:31:54,091
What you ask is... What you ask
is impossible. The cargo is legal.

409
00:31:54,200 --> 00:31:57,090
I have no grounds nor wish
to destroy civilian property.

410
00:31:57,200 --> 00:31:59,646
And now, madam, will you
leave me to my bath?

411
00:31:59,760 --> 00:32:02,047
Is it legal to sell whiskey to Indians?

412
00:32:02,160 --> 00:32:05,642
Who said anything...
Who said anything about Indians?

413
00:32:05,760 --> 00:32:08,491
The cargo is headed for Denver,
for businessmen there.

414
00:32:08,600 --> 00:32:11,570
- How do you know?
- I have the owner's word for it.

415
00:32:11,680 --> 00:32:14,331
Mr Frank Wallingham,
who is an acquaintance,

416
00:32:14,440 --> 00:32:16,966
a taxpayer, and a good Republican.

417
00:32:17,800 --> 00:32:21,247
Well, in that case,
you force me to take action.

418
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:25,289
Our movement has many friends
in many high places.

419
00:32:25,400 --> 00:32:28,006
Men such as... Horace Greeley.

420
00:32:31,920 --> 00:32:33,763
Is that a threat?

421
00:32:33,880 --> 00:32:37,362
You can consider it such if you like.
My conscience forces me to make it.

422
00:32:37,480 --> 00:32:39,642
And mine demands that I do my duty.

423
00:32:41,320 --> 00:32:43,288
So be it.

424
00:32:45,040 --> 00:32:49,807
May I impose upon your kindness for
directions to the post telegraph office?

425
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:53,688
Mrs Massingale, I'll do better than that.

426
00:32:53,800 --> 00:32:57,486
I'll furnish you transportation
to the Cheyenne telegraph office,

427
00:32:57,600 --> 00:33:01,082
where your messages are sure
to get out twice as quickly.

428
00:33:01,840 --> 00:33:02,443
Thank you.

429
00:33:02,560 --> 00:33:05,450
Call on me again if there's
anything further I can do.

430
00:33:05,560 --> 00:33:08,040
You're a very generous man, Colonel.

431
00:33:19,400 --> 00:33:21,368
Right tum! Ho!

432
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:51,606
Three telegrams, sir, just arrived.

433
00:33:54,600 --> 00:33:56,568
Read them.

434
00:33:57,760 --> 00:34:01,242
"The Governor of Colorado is
against liquor and its vicissitudes,

435
00:34:01,360 --> 00:34:04,170
but his position makes it impossible
to take a position

436
00:34:04,280 --> 00:34:06,851
in the matter of whiskey cargo to Denver."

437
00:34:07,560 --> 00:34:10,769
"The Adjutant General's office is
grateful to Women's Temperance

438
00:34:10,880 --> 00:34:15,647
for the splendid morale factor they have
upon the American soldier. However..."

439
00:34:15,760 --> 00:34:18,604
Whiskey matters must be left
to commanders in the field.

440
00:34:18,720 --> 00:34:20,688
"Respectfully."

441
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:25,207
"Mr Horace Greeley

442
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:28,642
has ever championed the noble cause
of temperance and suffrage,

443
00:34:28,760 --> 00:34:33,209
but is unable to interfere with
constituted authority of the West."

444
00:34:36,320 --> 00:34:39,802
Buell. Give these to Mrs Massingale
with my compliments

445
00:34:39,920 --> 00:34:43,686
and arrange transportation for her.
Her movement is moving.

446
00:34:44,440 --> 00:34:46,408
Yes, sir.

447
00:34:47,800 --> 00:34:49,609
<i>On the morning of November 16th,</i>

448
00:34:49,720 --> 00:34:55,170
<i>the Wallingham wagon train was moving
along north of the South Platte River.</i>

449
00:34:55,280 --> 00:34:58,648
<i>At the head was its owner,
Frank Wallingham,</i>

450
00:34:58,760 --> 00:35:01,809
<i>and its wagon master, Rafe Pike.</i>

451
00:35:02,320 --> 00:35:04,527
<i>To the rear was a group of Irish teamsters</i>

452
00:35:04,640 --> 00:35:08,122
<i>under the leadership
of one Kevin O'Flaherly.</i>

453
00:35:10,160 --> 00:35:12,322
<i>The Slater patrol was turning south</i>

454
00:35:12,440 --> 00:35:15,125
<i>towards the course
of the Wallingham train,</i>

455
00:35:15,240 --> 00:35:17,811
<i>and a band of Sioux warriors
was on the move,</i>

456
00:35:17,920 --> 00:35:20,526
<i>led by the great Chief 5 Barrels</i>

457
00:35:20,640 --> 00:35:23,644
<i>and his sub-chief, Walks-Stooped-Over,</i>

458
00:35:24,120 --> 00:35:28,205
<i>who was also known in certain
Indian circles as Sky Eyes,</i>

459
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:30,482
<i>due to the blue colour of his eyes,</i>

460
00:35:30,600 --> 00:35:36,403
<i>the heritage apparently of some slight,
uh... irregularity in his ancestry.</i>

461
00:35:36,920 --> 00:35:39,810
- Please, Father, be reasonable.
- No.

462
00:35:39,920 --> 00:35:43,811
If Mrs Massingale wants a farewell
meeting, she may use the mess hall.

463
00:35:43,920 --> 00:35:45,843
But I will not attend.

464
00:35:45,960 --> 00:35:48,167
But we're not asking you
to take the pledge.

465
00:35:48,280 --> 00:35:51,568
Although a bit of temperance
might make you happier.

466
00:35:51,680 --> 00:35:54,524
No red-blooded drinking man
is more temperate than I am.

467
00:35:54,640 --> 00:35:56,768
And I'm happy. I'm damned happy.

468
00:35:57,280 --> 00:35:59,851
If you would only try to
understand Mrs Massingale,

469
00:35:59,960 --> 00:36:02,167
a woman who's lost
two husbands to alcohol.

470
00:36:02,280 --> 00:36:04,806
They drank themselves
into an early grave.

471
00:36:04,920 --> 00:36:06,888
I can only wonder why.

472
00:36:07,760 --> 00:36:10,684
Do you absolutely refuse, Father,
to attend this meeting?

473
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:13,610
I do, and I'm beginning
to regret giving you the hall.

474
00:36:13,720 --> 00:36:16,007
The least you can do
is release the post band.

475
00:36:16,120 --> 00:36:16,609
No.

476
00:36:16,720 --> 00:36:19,041
- But we can't sing hymns without them.
- Good.

477
00:36:19,160 --> 00:36:21,640
- There's no point in having the meeting.
- Splendid.

478
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:23,728
Please, Father.

479
00:36:24,760 --> 00:36:29,288
It means so much to us.
And Mrs Massingale is leaving.

480
00:36:29,400 --> 00:36:31,368
We may never see her again.

481
00:36:32,520 --> 00:36:35,490
- Can I depend on that?
- Oh, I never go back on my word.

482
00:36:35,600 --> 00:36:38,046
I shall say goodbye at the meeting.

483
00:36:39,920 --> 00:36:42,730
Well, maybe the trombone.

484
00:36:42,840 --> 00:36:45,286
Thank you, Father. You're a dear.

485
00:36:45,400 --> 00:36:48,483
- And the drums?
- No. No drums.

486
00:36:50,440 --> 00:36:51,407
Good afternoon.

