936
01:19:31,720 --> 01:19:34,121
- Do you agree, Buell?
- Absolutely, sir.

937
01:19:34,240 --> 01:19:37,050
There are three important steps
to peace negotiations.

938
01:19:37,160 --> 01:19:39,925
No fraternisation
and no discharge of firearms.

939
01:19:40,040 --> 01:19:41,246
Yes, sir.

940
01:19:41,360 --> 01:19:45,524
- And the third step, sir?
- The third step? It's not important.

941
01:19:45,640 --> 01:19:49,725
What is important is to have a conference.
No peace without a conference, Slater.

942
01:19:49,840 --> 01:19:53,845
Buell, inform all interested parties
a conference will be held here

943
01:19:53,960 --> 01:19:56,327
- in one hour from now.
- Yes, sir.

944
01:19:59,360 --> 01:20:03,763
Beyond that, my contract - I got it here -
says that I am going to deliver,

945
01:20:03,880 --> 01:20:06,406
and I am gonna deliver,
come hell or high water.

946
01:20:06,520 --> 01:20:09,251
You gotta get them
damn foreigners outta here.

947
01:20:09,360 --> 01:20:12,409
- Mr Wallingham...
- I am a taxpayer and a good Republican,

948
01:20:12,520 --> 01:20:14,522
which means I am entitled to army escort.

949
01:20:14,640 --> 01:20:17,769
I'm damn well gonna get army escort
or I'm gonna raise hell...

950
01:20:17,880 --> 01:20:19,644
- Mr Wallingham.
- What?

951
01:20:19,760 --> 01:20:23,128
I will not tolerate profanity
in the presence of ladies.

952
01:20:24,480 --> 01:20:26,448
Oh...

953
01:20:27,440 --> 01:20:29,920
I think we understand
your position by now.

954
01:20:30,040 --> 01:20:33,806
The next party to be heard from
will be... uh... uh... Who are you?

955
01:20:34,680 --> 01:20:38,287
My name is Clayton Howell, sir,
commander of the Denver Free Militia.

956
01:20:38,400 --> 01:20:40,721
- What do you want?
- I'd like to inform the colonel

957
01:20:40,840 --> 01:20:44,640
that a lot of us here are members of
the Denver Saloon Owners' Association,

958
01:20:44,760 --> 01:20:48,048
and we intend to receive that there cargo
and take it home with us.

959
01:20:48,160 --> 01:20:50,561
The winter nights are
long and lonely in Denver,

960
01:20:50,680 --> 01:20:52,682
and a man is sorely in need of comfort.

961
01:20:52,800 --> 01:20:57,408
Startin' next month, that there sun
is gonna be a-settin' at 5.33pm,

962
01:20:57,520 --> 01:20:59,682
and she's gonna rise 11 dark hours later...

963
01:20:59,800 --> 01:21:02,804
All right. I think we can
leave the sun out of this.

964
01:21:03,960 --> 01:21:06,167
- What are you doing here, Oracle?
- Colonel.

965
01:21:06,280 --> 01:21:08,681
I'm the guide to the Denver Free Militia.

966
01:21:08,800 --> 01:21:12,486
It is my duty to see that this
precious cargo and these good people...

967
01:21:12,600 --> 01:21:16,366
Thank you, Oracle.
I'm well aware of the duties of a guide.

968
01:21:16,760 --> 01:21:19,730
- You're next.
- Kevin O'Flaherty at your service, sir.

969
01:21:19,840 --> 01:21:23,003
President of the Irish Teamsters.
With your permission,

970
01:21:23,120 --> 01:21:25,885
I have here a resolution
containing 14 points,

971
01:21:26,000 --> 01:21:28,810
which I'd like to read
prior to these labour negotiations.

972
01:21:28,920 --> 01:21:30,445
Labour negotiations?

973
01:21:30,560 --> 01:21:33,006
If our demands are not satisfied,
your lordship,

974
01:21:33,120 --> 01:21:35,805
we intend to strike,
as nasty as that may seem.

975
01:21:35,920 --> 01:21:38,526
- By damn, you just try...
- Wallingham!

976
01:21:39,320 --> 01:21:40,481
Oh.

977
01:21:40,600 --> 01:21:43,331
I am not gonna abandon
10 of my wagons to them Indians.

978
01:21:43,440 --> 01:21:47,809
Who said you had to? You've got the
Denver Free Militia to drive your wagons.

979
01:21:47,920 --> 01:21:49,843
What?

980
01:21:49,960 --> 01:21:51,644
Excuse me, sir.

981
01:21:51,760 --> 01:21:55,367
The militia couldn't do it, unless
we took a soldier to guard each wagon.

982
01:21:55,480 --> 01:22:00,611
- They're the worst bar flies in Denver.
- And who's gonna guard the soldiers?

983
01:22:00,720 --> 01:22:04,406
I see what you mean. Our supply of
temperance men is extremely limited.

984
01:22:04,520 --> 01:22:06,443
Yes, sir. It sure is.

985
01:22:07,360 --> 01:22:11,922
Well, since you have nothing further
to say, Mr O'Flaherty, sit down.

986
01:22:12,040 --> 01:22:15,010
- I call on Mrs Massingale.
- Thank you very much, Colonel.

987
01:22:15,120 --> 01:22:19,011
The temperance movement has now
spread right across this great nation.

988
01:22:19,120 --> 01:22:20,690
Founded in the year...

989
01:22:20,800 --> 01:22:23,724
Mrs Massingale, we are not here
for a history of the movement.

990
01:22:23,840 --> 01:22:26,411
- Have you anything further to say?
- I have.

991
01:22:26,520 --> 01:22:30,081
Dump it, I say. Dump this entire
vile cargo into the river right now.

992
01:22:30,200 --> 01:22:33,090
- By damn, madam...
- Mr Wallingham!

993
01:22:36,720 --> 01:22:38,768
<i>(speaks Sioux)</i>

994
01:22:49,160 --> 01:22:51,367
Did you get that, Captain?

995
01:22:51,480 --> 01:22:55,087
Not a word, but I have
an interpreter standing by. Sims!

996
01:22:57,840 --> 01:22:58,523
Yes, sir.

997
01:22:58,640 --> 01:23:03,009
Sims, find out what they're doing here,
why they left the reservation.

998
01:23:15,040 --> 01:23:18,123
<i>Hunt buffalo. Minding own business.</i>

999
01:23:18,680 --> 01:23:22,526
<i>Then white Long Knives come along
and attack peaceful Indian.</i>

1000
01:23:32,680 --> 01:23:34,842
<i>Paper say peaceful Indian.</i>

1001
01:23:36,520 --> 01:23:39,922
<i>We go home,
but first you give us presents.</i>

1002
01:23:43,240 --> 01:23:45,129
- What'd he say?
- He said.

1003
01:23:45,240 --> 01:23:48,084
"Hunt buffalo in peace,
minding their own business,

1004
01:23:48,200 --> 01:23:50,282
- when white Long Knives attack."
- What?

1005
01:23:50,400 --> 01:23:53,483
Yes, sir. But they're willin'
to go home now, sir.

1006
01:23:53,600 --> 01:23:57,047
- Well, tell him he's made a wise decision.
- Yes, sir.

1007
01:24:06,800 --> 01:24:09,451
Where are presents for us?

1008
01:24:10,160 --> 01:24:14,051
<i>You give me 20 wagons whiskey</i>

1009
01:24:14,160 --> 01:24:18,051
<i>or I' don't take my braves home.</i>

1010
01:24:18,640 --> 01:24:20,608
<i>Period.</i>

1011
01:24:25,440 --> 01:24:27,329
Yes? What'd he say?

1012
01:24:27,440 --> 01:24:30,728
He said he would like
to give you a present, sir.

1013
01:24:30,840 --> 01:24:32,842
- That's fine.
- But he hasn't got one, sir.

1014
01:24:32,960 --> 01:24:35,645
I see. Thank him, but tell him
no present is necessary.

1015
01:24:35,760 --> 01:24:37,728
Wait... I'll tell him.

1016
01:24:53,840 --> 01:24:58,243
All right, then. Tomorrow morning,
this whole, uh... this, uh...

1017
01:24:59,120 --> 01:25:00,485
We're leaving for Denver.

1018
01:25:00,600 --> 01:25:04,321
You will take your orders from
Sergeant Major Buell as to starting time,

1019
01:25:04,440 --> 01:25:07,364
disposition of marching order,
camp sites, et cetera.

1020
01:25:07,480 --> 01:25:10,051
Any decisions to be made
will be made by me.

1021
01:25:10,840 --> 01:25:13,571
- Sergeant.
- Conference stands adjourned!

1022
01:25:52,520 --> 01:25:54,488
- Buell.
- Yes, sir?

1023
01:25:55,080 --> 01:25:57,048
What are those Indians doing here?

1024
01:25:57,160 --> 01:26:00,846
- I don't know, sir.
- How long have they been following us?

1025
01:26:00,960 --> 01:26:04,328
I was gonna bring that matter
to the colonel's attention.

1026
01:26:04,440 --> 01:26:09,401
They've been trailing us all day, sir.
Shall I take a squad and run 'em off, sir?

1027
01:26:10,040 --> 01:26:14,125
Buell, the Indian wars are over. These
Sioux are wards of the government.

1028
01:26:14,240 --> 01:26:18,325
- How would that look in Washington?
- The colonel has a point, sir.

1029
01:26:18,440 --> 01:26:23,207
Get the interpreter. Find out why they're
still here. And we'll camp early tonight.

1030
01:26:23,320 --> 01:26:26,642
- Field quarters assembly?
- Have the sentries out before dark.

1031
01:26:30,200 --> 01:26:34,250
Carter, check the rest of the sentries
and find Sergeant Buell.

1032
01:26:51,800 --> 01:26:53,768
<i>(water splashing)</i>

1033
01:27:23,440 --> 01:27:25,807
Phillips, what's going on here?

1034
01:27:25,920 --> 01:27:28,048
Compliments of Mrs Massingale, sir.

1035
01:27:28,160 --> 01:27:32,848
She has use of another tub, sir, and
she thought the colonel looked dirty, sir.

1036
01:27:32,960 --> 01:27:35,645
Kind of scroungy and mucky, sir.

1037
01:27:36,520 --> 01:27:38,761
And she thought... she sort of...

1038
01:27:40,760 --> 01:27:42,285
Yes, sir.

1039
01:27:52,560 --> 01:27:54,881
- Colonel Gearhart, sir.
- Yes?

1040
01:27:55,400 --> 01:28:00,804
All sentries on their posts, sir. The Denver
militia has retired for the evening.

1041
01:28:00,920 --> 01:28:05,767
- Where's Sergeant Buell?
- At the Indian camp with the interpreter.

1042
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:09,241
- That's all, Carter.
- Yes, sir.

1043
01:28:21,080 --> 01:28:24,402
<i>- Sh'?
- Come 'm, Hue“.</i>

1044
01:28:25,920 --> 01:28:28,366
The report from the interpreter, sir...

1045
01:28:28,480 --> 01:28:30,528
He, uh...

1046
01:28:32,160 --> 01:28:34,128
Well?

1047
01:28:34,680 --> 01:28:36,808
There might be a little confusion, sir.

1048
01:28:36,920 --> 01:28:39,082
- Confusion?
- Confusion. Yes, sir.

1049
01:28:39,200 --> 01:28:42,602
The interpreter was only sure they said
"Hunt buffalo in peace,

1050
01:28:42,720 --> 01:28:45,929
minding own business,
when white Long Knives attack."

1051
01:28:46,040 --> 01:28:50,011
"Willing to go home.
Would like to give you present."

1052
01:28:54,160 --> 01:28:56,527
Sergeant, get me Oracle Jones.

1053
01:28:57,760 --> 01:28:59,728
Yes, sir.

1054
01:29:16,320 --> 01:29:18,288
Friend.

1055
01:29:20,320 --> 01:29:24,689
Go ahead. Don't beat around the bush.
Find out why the hell they're still here.

1056
01:29:24,800 --> 01:29:26,768
<i>(Oracle and chief speak Sioux)</i>

1057
01:29:31,880 --> 01:29:34,042
He says he's waitin' for the presents.

1058
01:29:34,160 --> 01:29:36,128
Presents? Wait a...

1059
01:29:37,040 --> 01:29:40,249
Well, tell him we don't want
any presents, and thank him.

1060
01:29:40,360 --> 01:29:42,328
<i>(speaks Sioux)</i>

1061
01:29:49,800 --> 01:29:52,201
Not for you, Colonel. For him.

1062
01:29:54,320 --> 01:29:59,929
Just a minute. He said "Hunt buffalo
in peace, minding own business..."

1063
01:30:00,520 --> 01:30:02,363
- Sims!
- Yes, sir.

1064
01:30:02,480 --> 01:30:05,563
- You're under arrest.
- Yes, sir.

1065
01:30:10,920 --> 01:30:14,891
- Suppose I refuse to give them presents?
- They won't go home.

1066
01:30:18,320 --> 01:30:20,288
Well, find out what they want.

1067
01:30:21,640 --> 01:30:23,802
<i>(speaks Sioux)</i>

1068
01:30:29,360 --> 01:30:35,163
The chief says he wants 20 wagons of...
<i>minne wakan</i>... crazy water.

1069
01:30:36,240 --> 01:30:38,208
20 wagons of whiskey?

1070
01:30:38,320 --> 01:30:42,006
That chief... he's a real boozer, Colonel.

1071
01:30:43,480 --> 01:30:45,767
Well, you tell him no.

1072
01:30:45,880 --> 01:30:48,486
No one's gonna blackmail
the United States Army!

1073
01:30:48,600 --> 01:30:53,640
Tell him to pack up his braves and get
back where they come from. I'll tell him.

1074
01:30:54,520 --> 01:30:58,844
White chief... Indian chief...
meet... as friends.

1075
01:31:00,080 --> 01:31:02,082
Leave as friends.

1076
01:31:02,200 --> 01:31:04,646
No crazy water, no whiskey.

1077
01:31:04,760 --> 01:31:07,730
Go home in peace... But go home!

1078
01:31:07,840 --> 01:31:09,808
- Sergeant.
- Yes, sir.

1079
01:31:38,280 --> 01:31:40,248
<i>(dripping)</i>

1080
01:31:50,440 --> 01:31:52,408
<i>(moans)</i>

1081
01:32:00,440 --> 01:32:02,408
<i>(snoring)</i>

1082
01:32:26,880 --> 01:32:28,848
<i>(upping)</i>

1083
01:32:28,960 --> 01:32:30,928
<i>(liquid pouring)</i>

1084
01:33:02,360 --> 01:33:04,328
<i>(Oracle laughs)</i>

1085
01:33:12,360 --> 01:33:15,250
<i>♪ Hallelujah!</i>

1086
01:33:16,200 --> 01:33:17,804
There! Now I see it!

1087
01:33:23,520 --> 01:33:25,488
(snares)

1088
01:33:39,080 --> 01:33:41,651
Frank! Hold up there, Frank!

1089
01:33:42,920 --> 01:33:48,450
Frank, come sundown you head your
wagons in towards Quicksand Bottoms.

1090
01:33:48,560 --> 01:33:50,528
- Why?
- We'll be campin' there tonight.

1091
01:33:50,640 --> 01:33:52,688
No, we ain't. Not this train.

1092
01:33:52,800 --> 01:33:57,203
- Well, sure, Frank. You just suit yourself.
- That's a waste of time and horsepower.

1093
01:33:57,320 --> 01:34:00,290
I'll just light out for Denver
on my lonesome.

1094
01:34:03,040 --> 01:34:05,202
Wait a minute, Oracle.
You seen somethin'?

1095
01:34:05,320 --> 01:34:10,087
Well now, I don't mind tellin' you
things is just beginnin' to come through.

1096
01:34:10,200 --> 01:34:12,567
- What? What?
- Can't say.

1097
01:34:13,960 --> 01:34:16,122
Got somethin' to do
with Quicksand Bottoms?

1098
01:34:16,240 --> 01:34:17,730
Yep.

1099
01:34:17,840 --> 01:34:22,687
Rafe! Rafe! When we get to
Quicksand Bottoms, head in.

1100
01:34:22,800 --> 01:34:26,327
- We're gonna camp there tonight.
- Huh?

1101
01:34:26,440 --> 01:34:30,126
When we get to Quicksand Bottoms,
head in. We're gonna camp there tonight.

1102
01:34:30,240 --> 01:34:32,208
OK, Frank.

1103
01:34:41,040 --> 01:34:43,202
Militia, halt!

1104
01:34:46,400 --> 01:34:48,971
Get that circle formed in there
and keep it tight.

1105
01:34:49,080 --> 01:34:51,560
Stay away from the edge
of that swamp. Look out!

1106
01:34:51,680 --> 01:34:54,729
Come on, move it up there.
Close it up tight!

1107
01:34:57,280 --> 01:35:00,170
Stay away from the edge
of that swamp. Look out!

1108
01:35:00,880 --> 01:35:02,848
<i>(gurgling)</i>

1109
01:35:04,520 --> 01:35:07,683
All right! All right!
Come on, the rest of ya! Watch out!

1110
01:35:07,960 --> 01:35:09,928
Frank! You'd better come quick!

1111
01:35:10,040 --> 01:35:13,886
The Irish have gone on strike
and they've taken 10 of the wagons.

1112
01:35:20,960 --> 01:35:25,409
Clayton! Go and rescue
that precious booze. Form up your men.

1113
01:35:25,520 --> 01:35:28,649
Militia! Form up in a column of fours! Hup!

1114
01:35:33,680 --> 01:35:36,081
Sir, the teamsters have
finally gone on strike.

1115
01:35:36,200 --> 01:35:38,521
They've taken 10 wagons
and formed a circle.

1116
01:35:38,640 --> 01:35:42,201
- Where's Wallingham?
- He's gettin' the militia together, sir.

1117
01:35:42,320 --> 01:35:44,482
I've put a platoon
between them and the ladies.

1118
01:35:44,600 --> 01:35:47,604
- The ladies?
- They're supporting the strike, sir.

1119
01:35:47,720 --> 01:35:50,690
It's quite possible
that violence is imminent.

1120
01:36:04,200 --> 01:36:06,328
Come down from there, you alien radical!

1121
01:36:06,440 --> 01:36:08,204
- Capitalist!
- Anarchist!

1122
01:36:08,320 --> 01:36:10,288
Hold your positions, ladies.

1123
01:36:21,800 --> 01:36:26,408
You finally got here, did ya? I want you
to get this damn mess straightened out.

1124
01:36:32,840 --> 01:36:36,447
You! Just what are you
and your ladies up to this time?

1125
01:36:37,200 --> 01:36:40,170
Merely exercising our right
to peaceful assembly,

1126
01:36:40,280 --> 01:36:45,730
as guaranteed by the Constitution, which
you, an army officer, are sworn to uphold.

1127
01:36:47,480 --> 01:36:48,447
O'Flaherty.

1128
01:36:48,560 --> 01:36:50,642
We're just honest workmen,
your lordship,

1129
01:36:50,760 --> 01:36:54,367
exercising our God-given right
to refuse to work.

1130
01:36:54,480 --> 01:36:58,371
Hah! You're a pack of cowards,
hidin' behind the skirts of these women.

1131
01:36:58,480 --> 01:37:02,326
Besides that, you're a pack of Irish
thieves. They stole 10 of my wagons.

1132
01:37:02,440 --> 01:37:06,331
- I demand you do somethin' about it.
- Now, calm yourself, Mr Wallingham.

1133
01:37:06,440 --> 01:37:09,330
I can see your wagons.
They don't look stolen to me.

1134
01:37:09,440 --> 01:37:11,761
Well, they're as good as stolen, by damn!

1135
01:37:11,880 --> 01:37:14,406
I must remind you, sir,
there are ladies present.

1136
01:37:14,520 --> 01:37:17,046
Damn right they're present.
I want 'em removed.

1137
01:37:17,160 --> 01:37:20,721
I'm sorry, Mr Wallingham,
but this is obviously a labour dispute.

1138
01:37:20,840 --> 01:37:25,721
Much as I hate to admit it, Mrs Massingale
and Mr O'Flaherty are within their rights.

1139
01:37:25,840 --> 01:37:29,083
What about my rights
as a taxpayer and a good Republican?

1140
01:37:29,200 --> 01:37:32,921
I'll protect your wagons and cargo,
but under army regulations I cannot...

1141
01:37:33,040 --> 01:37:36,249
All right, men. Enough of this
tin-soldier lawyer talk.

1142
01:37:36,360 --> 01:37:40,524
Club down them lrishmen.
Club 'em down and tote them women out.

1143
01:37:41,640 --> 01:37:46,521
Slater, take charge. You'll meet force with
force to whatever extent is necessary.

1144
01:37:46,640 --> 01:37:49,723
Companies A and B, move up! Ho!

1145
01:38:00,960 --> 01:38:03,327
Draw carbines! Ho!

1146
01:38:06,960 --> 01:38:09,850
Come on, get in there!
What are you waitin' for?

1147
01:38:10,760 --> 01:38:12,888
Uh... be reasonable, Frank.

1148
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:16,368
We can't fight the United States Army.
It wouldn't look good.

1149
01:38:19,080 --> 01:38:23,563
All right, Gearhart. I'm holding you
responsible for every one of my wagons.

1150
01:38:23,680 --> 01:38:26,650
- I accept the responsibility. Buell!
- Sir!

1151
01:38:26,760 --> 01:38:31,129
- We'll camp here tonight. Pick a site.
- Yes, sir. Field order 138, sir?

1152
01:38:34,280 --> 01:38:36,248
Yes, sir.

1153
01:38:37,280 --> 01:38:42,047
My congratulations, Mrs Massingale. A
brilliant manoeuvre, flawlessly executed.

1154
01:38:42,160 --> 01:38:44,447
Thank you, Colonel. I'm very flattered.

1155
01:38:45,360 --> 01:38:47,328
Maintain order, Slater.

1156
01:39:03,360 --> 01:39:05,283
Ladies.

1157
01:39:05,400 --> 01:39:07,368
Mrs Massingale, ma'am...

1158
01:39:08,080 --> 01:39:11,527
Would you mind telling me just what
you expect to gain by all this?

1159
01:39:11,640 --> 01:39:13,130
Time, for one thing.

1160
01:39:13,240 --> 01:39:15,846
But you can't keep my wagons
immobilised for ever.

1161
01:39:15,960 --> 01:39:18,122
We'll see.

1162
01:39:18,240 --> 01:39:21,562
Would you mind telling me
what your next move might be?

1163
01:39:21,680 --> 01:39:25,162
Well, apart from our non-violent
picket line, we have no plans.

1164
01:39:25,280 --> 01:39:27,965
Except to have our meeting
at the Indian camp tonight.

1165
01:39:28,080 --> 01:39:30,048
- A what?
- A rally.

1166
01:39:30,160 --> 01:39:31,889
A rally, Frank.

1167
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:35,083
Hold your positions, ladies.
Come along, Louise.

1168
01:39:37,000 --> 01:39:39,162
A rally at the Indian camp.

1169
01:39:41,040 --> 01:39:42,565
♪ We will save, we will save,

1170
01:39:42,920 --> 01:39:47,960
♪ we will save another soul, hallelujah

1171
01:39:48,240 --> 01:39:54,600
♪ We will save, we will save,
we will save another soul

1172
01:39:54,720 --> 01:39:58,247
♪ And if the road is rocky
and a man should start to slip

1173
01:39:58,880 --> 01:40:01,645
♪ Man should start to slip,
man should start to slip

1174
01:40:01,760 --> 01:40:05,321
♪ And if the road is rocky
and a man should start to slip

1175
01:40:05,440 --> 01:40:08,842
♪ We will take a better grip

1176
01:40:08,960 --> 01:40:12,407
♪ And if a man gets weak
and takes a bottle from the shelf

1177
01:40:13,040 --> 01:40:15,805
♪ Bottle from the shelf,
bottle from the shelf

1178
01:40:15,920 --> 01:40:19,447
♪ And if a man gets weak
and takes a bottle from the shelf

1179
01:40:19,760 --> 01:40:23,003
♪ We will save him from himself

1180
01:40:23,720 --> 01:40:25,165
♪ We will save...

1181
01:40:25,280 --> 01:40:27,248
<i>(speaks Sioux)</i>

1182
01:40:31,080 --> 01:40:37,531
♪ We will save, we will save,
we will save another soul

1183
01:40:37,640 --> 01:40:41,326
♪ And if the road is rocky
and a man should start to slip

1184
01:40:41,560 --> 01:40:43,642
♪ Man should start to slip...

1185
01:40:43,760 --> 01:40:46,764
- What'd he say?
- He says, uh...

1186
01:40:46,880 --> 01:40:50,089
"Good to sign white squaw's paper.
Good for peace."

1187
01:40:52,440 --> 01:40:58,800
♪ We will save, we will save,
we will save another soul

1188
01:40:58,920 --> 01:41:02,481
♪ And if the road is rocky
and a man should start to slip

1189
01:41:03,040 --> 01:41:05,930
♪ Man should start to slip,
man should start to slip...

1190
01:41:06,040 --> 01:41:08,008
<i>(band joins in)</i>

1191
01:41:17,600 --> 01:41:22,640
if it's the last thing I ever do, I'll have
that entire band transferred to Alaska.

1192
01:41:27,920 --> 01:41:29,968
- What are they doing now?
- Singing, sir.

1193
01:41:30,080 --> 01:41:33,209
- And signing pledges.
- I don't believe it.

1194
01:41:33,320 --> 01:41:35,846
As far as I can tell,
they've got 50 signed already.

1195
01:41:35,960 --> 01:41:40,124
Go back there, Sergeant. Get me
one of those pledges. I wanna see it.

1196
01:41:41,120 --> 01:41:43,088
How can I get one, sir?

1197
01:41:44,880 --> 01:41:47,087
Yes, sir!

1198
01:41:47,200 --> 01:41:53,082
♪ We will save, we will save,
we will save another soul

1199
01:41:53,640 --> 01:41:57,042
♪ And if a man is saved,
there are others still to come...

1200
01:41:57,920 --> 01:42:01,527
- Can you handle the rest of this, Louise?
- You can count on me, Mrs Massingale.

1201
01:42:01,640 --> 01:42:03,688
I'm gonna hand out
equipment to Group B.

1202
01:42:03,800 --> 01:42:05,768
Good luck, Cora.

1203
01:42:09,440 --> 01:42:13,206
Here, sir. Just a crazy mark,
but each one of 'em's marked different.

1204
01:42:13,320 --> 01:42:15,800
That woman! How many?

1205
01:42:15,920 --> 01:42:17,888
- 81 now, sir.
- 81?

1206
01:42:19,560 --> 01:42:22,723
Get back there, Buell.
And tell Slater to cover his flanks.

1207
01:42:22,840 --> 01:42:24,126
Yes, sir.

1208
01:42:25,080 --> 01:42:27,048
Chisel.

1209
01:42:28,160 --> 01:42:30,367
Axe.

1210
01:42:30,480 --> 01:42:32,369
Hammer.

1211
01:42:35,720 --> 01:42:37,802
Where's that Massingale woman?

1212
01:42:37,920 --> 01:42:42,050
She's down there somewhere, Frank,
takin' advantage of ignorant savages.

1213
01:42:42,160 --> 01:42:45,881
- There oughta be a law agin it.
- There oughta be somethin'.

1214
01:42:46,000 --> 01:42:49,971
- I don't trust her.
- You just keep your pants hitched, Frank.

1215
01:42:56,160 --> 01:42:58,128
<i>(gunfire)</i>

1216
01:43:08,120 --> 01:43:11,283
Chief says... "No more peace."

1217
01:43:14,800 --> 01:43:18,122
What is it, Sergeant?
What happened, Sergeant?

1218
01:43:18,240 --> 01:43:20,481
- The Indians have captured the women.
- What?

1219
01:43:20,600 --> 01:43:23,285
One minute they were all
signing pledges and then...

1220
01:43:23,400 --> 01:43:25,607
How did that idiot Slater
ever let it happen?

1221
01:43:25,720 --> 01:43:28,849
On behalf of Captain Slater, sir,
it's only fair to state

1222
01:43:28,960 --> 01:43:34,126
that if the women hadn't started singing
hymns and making all that... racket...

1223
01:43:39,040 --> 01:43:42,203
Sir, the Indians disarmed my men
and took the ladies captive.

1224
01:43:42,320 --> 01:43:44,243
I know what they did, Slater.

1225
01:43:44,360 --> 01:43:48,001
They moved fast, we were outnumbered,
there was nothing I could do.

1226
01:43:48,120 --> 01:43:49,724
- Sergeant.
- Sir!

1227
01:43:49,840 --> 01:43:52,571
Alert the bugler. Rouse the camp.
Prepare for battle.

1228
01:43:52,680 --> 01:43:58,050
Yes, sir! Sir, any rash move on our part
may endanger the lives of the women.

1229
01:43:58,160 --> 01:44:01,403
- Dammit, I can't just twiddle my thumbs.
- No, sir!

1230
01:44:01,520 --> 01:44:03,522
Sir, the sergeant's right, sir.

1231
01:44:03,640 --> 01:44:07,281
An attack right now might be
most ill-advised... sir.

1232
01:44:10,240 --> 01:44:12,686
- Why is he here?
- He's a symbol of their good faith.

1233
01:44:12,800 --> 01:44:14,609
Good faith?

1234
01:44:14,720 --> 01:44:17,200
- They wanna bargain with us.
- Bargain?

1235
01:44:17,320 --> 01:44:20,642
20 wagons of whiskey
in exchange for the women.

1236
01:44:20,760 --> 01:44:23,969
- 20 wagons?
- Yes, sir. You see, the Indians...

1237
01:44:26,680 --> 01:44:29,126
- Can he understand us?
- Not a word, sir.

1238
01:44:29,240 --> 01:44:31,846
20 wagons comes out to about...

1239
01:44:32,840 --> 01:44:35,446
three and seven-eighths women
per wagon.

1240
01:44:35,560 --> 01:44:38,689
I think that was it, or maybe
the interpreter was confused.

1241
01:44:38,800 --> 01:44:39,767
- Slater.
- Yes, sir.

1242
01:44:39,880 --> 01:44:43,965
There's only one course of action now.
I am declaring martial law!

1243
01:44:46,240 --> 01:44:51,246
I say you can't do it! No tinhorn colonel's
gonna come here and declare martial law.

1244
01:44:51,360 --> 01:44:54,523
If you don't shut up, Mr Wallingham,
my first step will be to lock you up.

1245
01:44:54,640 --> 01:44:57,723
Gentlemen, this bickering
can lead to nothing constructive.

1246
01:44:57,840 --> 01:45:01,162
Since you cannot take
military action against the Indians

1247
01:45:01,280 --> 01:45:05,683
and you cannot negotiate with them, there
is only one course of action open to us.

1248
01:45:05,800 --> 01:45:09,600
We must accede to their demands
and give them the whiskey without delay.

1249
01:45:09,720 --> 01:45:12,007
Giving whiskey to Indians
is strictly forbidden

1250
01:45:12,120 --> 01:45:15,169
by the army regulations
so dear to you, Mrs Massingale.

1251
01:45:15,280 --> 01:45:17,521
Not if the Indians don't drink the whiskey.

1252
01:45:17,640 --> 01:45:20,166
What's to stop the Indians
from drinking whiskey?

1253
01:45:20,280 --> 01:45:21,770
Precisely.

1254
01:45:21,880 --> 01:45:25,009
I have their pledges.
One hundred signed pledges

1255
01:45:25,120 --> 01:45:29,170
with this one on the top signed by
Chief 5 Barrels himself. That's his mark.

1256
01:45:29,280 --> 01:45:31,601
She's right. That's his mark.

1257
01:45:31,720 --> 01:45:33,449
Do they get the whiskey?

1258
01:45:33,560 --> 01:45:36,530
It's my whiskey, and you're not
going to touch one drop of it!

1259
01:45:36,640 --> 01:45:38,483
- Listen, Frank...
- Quiet!

1260
01:45:38,600 --> 01:45:42,685
In that case, I have no choice but to
destroy all the whiskey right now.

1261
01:45:42,800 --> 01:45:44,245
You're bluff in'.

1262
01:45:44,360 --> 01:45:46,601
Oh...

1263
01:45:46,720 --> 01:45:48,688
Am I?

1264
01:45:49,200 --> 01:45:52,249
There is a woman hidden in each
and every one of those wagons,

1265
01:45:52,360 --> 01:45:56,649
awaiting my order by code to start
smashing the barrels of this vile cargo.

1266
01:45:56,760 --> 01:45:58,967
Madam, you lie.

1267
01:45:59,080 --> 01:46:00,730
Indeed?

1268
01:46:04,320 --> 01:46:06,482
Ladies of Group B...

1269
01:46:09,640 --> 01:46:11,802
Frank, will you keep your pants hitched?

1270
01:46:11,920 --> 01:46:17,211
The signal was to be a hymn, but that's
not necessary. I'll just tell them to begin.

1271
01:46:17,320 --> 01:46:20,802
- You wouldn't do that.
- Ladies of Group B, you may begin!

1272
01:46:20,920 --> 01:46:23,048
Puncture those barrels!

1273
01:46:23,160 --> 01:46:25,766
- No, wait!
- Just a moment, ladies!

1274
01:46:28,920 --> 01:46:34,131
You let her smash one barrel and I'll have
those brass buttons ripped off your chest!

1275
01:46:34,240 --> 01:46:37,722
- I'm a taxpayer and a good Republican!
- You say that one more time

1276
01:46:37,840 --> 01:46:40,366
and I'll bust you right in the nose!

1277
01:46:40,480 --> 01:46:43,006
- Are you threatening me?
- Now sit down!

1278
01:46:43,120 --> 01:46:46,488
- You hear that?
- Sit down! Come on, Frank. Sit down.

1279
01:46:49,840 --> 01:46:52,002
And shut up!

1280
01:46:54,480 --> 01:46:56,801
Mrs Massingale, sit down.

1281
01:46:58,520 --> 01:47:00,488
Sit down!

1282
01:47:07,920 --> 01:47:10,082
And stay down.

1283
01:47:23,720 --> 01:47:26,644
Ladies of Group B,
get out of those wagons!

1284
01:47:27,160 --> 01:47:29,128
Right now!

1285
01:47:41,600 --> 01:47:43,807
- Sergeant, put this down.
- Yes, sir.

1286
01:47:43,920 --> 01:47:48,164
The United States Army confiscates
20 wagons of the Wallingham train.

1287
01:47:48,280 --> 01:47:51,124
There! You hear that?
Confiscation of private property,

1288
01:47:51,240 --> 01:47:54,961
in which case I shall be repaid in full.
Go ahead, declare martial law.

1289
01:47:55,080 --> 01:47:58,527
- Martial law to take effect at daybreak.
- You declare it right now!

1290
01:47:58,640 --> 01:48:01,450
Don't you tell me
when to declare martial law.

1291
01:48:02,360 --> 01:48:06,410
Slater. Take that symbol of good faith
back to Chief 5 Barrels.

1292
01:48:06,520 --> 01:48:09,126
And, Slater, knock down the price.

1293
01:48:13,640 --> 01:48:15,847
- Buell.
- Sir!

1294
01:48:15,960 --> 01:48:17,928
This meeting stands adjourned.

1295
01:48:26,720 --> 01:48:28,051
Get outta here!

1296
01:48:28,160 --> 01:48:30,925
Go on! Get outta here,
you bunch of vandals!

1297
01:48:31,040 --> 01:48:33,008
Get off of my property!

1298
01:48:33,600 --> 01:48:35,762
Get off of my bed! Get outta here!

1299
01:48:53,560 --> 01:48:56,882
Get outta that wagon! Get outta there!

1300
01:48:58,680 --> 01:49:00,648
Out! Out!

1301
01:49:11,520 --> 01:49:13,488
<i>(laughs)</i>

1302
01:49:16,040 --> 01:49:19,089
I thought I heard ya, Frank. (Chuckles)

1303
01:49:19,200 --> 01:49:20,122
He, he, he...

1304
01:49:20,240 --> 01:49:22,607
You got me into this, you soothsaying sot.

1305
01:49:22,720 --> 01:49:26,691
And now I'll get you out of it, Frank.
In fact, it's all set.

1306
01:49:26,800 --> 01:49:30,646
Everything's ready, except one
more chore I gotta do right now.

1307
01:49:30,760 --> 01:49:34,481
Believe me, Frank,
you just trust old Oracle.

1308
01:49:34,600 --> 01:49:37,285
Me and my Billy girl is gonna fix it all up.

1309
01:49:37,920 --> 01:49:41,686
Come on now, Billy girl.
Take me slow and take me true.

1310
01:49:56,760 --> 01:49:59,081
<i>(liquid pouring)</i>

1311
01:50:10,160 --> 01:50:12,128
<i>(Mrs Massingale) Colonel?</i>

1312
01:50:12,880 --> 01:50:14,848
Go away!

1313
01:50:17,640 --> 01:50:19,722
Madam, I don't know what you're up to,

1314
01:50:19,840 --> 01:50:22,650
but whatever it is
I don't wanna hear about it.

1315
01:50:23,400 --> 01:50:26,529
I've come to tell you how truly sorry
I am for what I've done.

1316
01:50:26,640 --> 01:50:28,927
Thank you, and good night.

1317
01:50:29,040 --> 01:50:31,281
Colonel, do you realise what will happen

1318
01:50:31,400 --> 01:50:35,564
when word gets out that you've given
20 wagons of whiskey to Sioux Indians?

1319
01:50:35,680 --> 01:50:37,409
I realise!

1320
01:50:37,520 --> 01:50:40,967
20 wagons confiscated from
a taxpayer and a good Republican.

1321
01:50:41,080 --> 01:50:44,004
Don't you tell me what he is
or I'll bust you on the nose!

1322
01:50:44,120 --> 01:50:48,330
- Colonel, those cords again. Just let me...
- Get away from my cords!

1323
01:50:48,440 --> 01:50:51,011
If you just relax and let the blood flow...

1324
01:50:51,120 --> 01:50:53,282
My blood can flow on its own.

1325
01:50:55,080 --> 01:50:58,402
Mrs Massingale, I don't know
what your plans are for tomorrow,

1326
01:50:58,520 --> 01:51:01,410
but judging from experience,
you'd better get some rest.

1327
01:51:01,520 --> 01:51:04,603
How can I rest
after what I've done to you?

1328
01:51:04,720 --> 01:51:06,688
Try!

1329
01:51:17,040 --> 01:51:19,008
<i>(sobbing)</i>

1330
01:51:23,800 --> 01:51:25,768
Oh...

1331
01:51:41,480 --> 01:51:45,166
My selfishness, my obstinacy,

1332
01:51:45,280 --> 01:51:47,965
my stupidity in not listening
to your advice.

1333
01:51:48,080 --> 01:51:49,809
I must agree with you.

1334
01:51:49,920 --> 01:51:54,721
- It's all my fault you're in this position.
- Well, crying isn't going to help.

1335
01:52:09,840 --> 01:52:11,729
Mrs Massingale...

1336
01:52:15,360 --> 01:52:17,522
Mrs Massingale!

1337
01:52:17,640 --> 01:52:19,608
You needn't look so shocked.

1338
01:52:20,520 --> 01:52:24,286
Plato, Augustus, Alexander...

1339
01:52:24,800 --> 01:52:29,249
even George Washington took
occasional spirits in medicinal amounts.

1340
01:52:31,040 --> 01:52:35,409
There's nothing wrong with limited
libation under emotional stress.

1341
01:52:38,720 --> 01:52:41,087
Your entire career is ruined!

1342
01:52:42,680 --> 01:52:45,809
Well... I suppose
there'll be some criticism.

1343
01:52:46,120 --> 01:52:48,361
Criticism? You'll be crucified!

1344
01:52:49,560 --> 01:52:52,689
The press, the public,
the War Department.

1345
01:52:53,480 --> 01:52:55,448
Horace Greeley.

1346
01:52:56,640 --> 01:52:58,608
Oh...

1347
01:53:08,040 --> 01:53:13,524
Well, if I can save the lives of 27 women,
I... I'd gladly sacrifice my career.

1348
01:53:13,640 --> 01:53:17,167
After all, what is it?
Only 19 years of service.

1349
01:53:17,640 --> 01:53:20,723
With Grant at Vicksburg.
With Thomas at Nashville.

1350
01:53:20,840 --> 01:53:24,003
17 Indian campaigns,
Laramie to Fort Hall.

1351
01:53:25,920 --> 01:53:27,888
One more year.

1352
01:53:28,600 --> 01:53:32,764
281 dollars and 25 cents a month,
pension.

1353
01:53:33,840 --> 01:53:37,526
Sergeant Buell,
27 dollars and 50 cents a month.

1354
01:53:38,960 --> 01:53:41,167
Every month.

1355
01:53:41,280 --> 01:53:43,248
19 years.

1356
01:53:45,240 --> 01:53:48,926
And all that time, not once have I ever...

1357
01:53:49,040 --> 01:53:52,328
never have I ever met anyone like...

1358
01:53:52,840 --> 01:53:55,002
Like me?

1359
01:53:56,480 --> 01:53:59,768
Oh, well, I'll just resign gracefully.
Anyway, I'll resign.

1360
01:54:00,920 --> 01:54:03,571
Well, at least you'll still
have your beloved West.

1361
01:54:03,680 --> 01:54:05,842
- I hate the West.
- Oh, dear!

1362
01:54:05,960 --> 01:54:08,327
Dust, wind, Indians.

1363
01:54:10,200 --> 01:54:14,569
My stubbornness, my obstinacy,
my selfishness.

1364
01:54:14,680 --> 01:54:17,001
Now, now, Cora... uh... Mrs Massingale.

1365
01:54:17,120 --> 01:54:19,327
If only I'd listened to you. If only!

1366
01:54:19,800 --> 01:54:22,724
Easy, easy, Mrs Massingale... Cora.

1367
01:54:22,840 --> 01:54:25,684
Do you think you could
ever forgive me, Thaddeus?

1368
01:54:26,800 --> 01:54:28,962
Well, l...

1369
01:54:40,920 --> 01:54:43,605
I could try.

1370
01:54:50,680 --> 01:54:52,648
Cora...

1371
01:54:53,360 --> 01:54:56,364
Couldn't we forget all this? I mean...

1372
01:54:58,240 --> 01:55:03,326
I mean... just forget
the whole thing... Cora?

1373
01:55:03,440 --> 01:55:06,205
- Colonel Gearhart!
- One moment, Slater.

1374
01:55:16,440 --> 01:55:18,408
Come in, Slater.

1375
01:55:21,320 --> 01:55:26,565
- Captain Slater reporting, sir.
- ♪ Stand up, we'll march to Denver.

1376
01:55:27,480 --> 01:55:31,041
- ♪ No more wine or beer.
- Someone's singing. Go on, Slater.

1377
01:55:31,840 --> 01:55:34,446
Uh... Chief 5 Barrels
said he'd take 15 barrels.

1378
01:55:34,560 --> 01:55:36,767
I came back with eight and he said 13.

1379
01:55:37,440 --> 01:55:41,286
I think that was the number.
The language barrier is very difficult, sir.

1380
01:55:41,400 --> 01:55:44,563
- Did you reach any agreement?
- 10 wagons of whiskey.

1381
01:55:44,680 --> 01:55:46,170
- 10 wagons?
- For all the women.

1382
01:55:46,280 --> 01:55:48,123
- Good work, Slater.
- Thank you, sir.

1383
01:55:48,240 --> 01:55:52,165
- What's he doing here?
- The same, sir. A symbol of good faith.

1384
01:55:56,760 --> 01:55:59,240
Are you sure he can't understand us?

1385
01:55:59,360 --> 01:56:01,601
- Not a word.
- That's all, Slater.

1386
01:56:06,040 --> 01:56:10,682
Oh... The Indians
would like to have... uh...

1387
01:56:10,800 --> 01:56:13,883
Mrs Massingale present
for the exchange, sir.

1388
01:56:15,920 --> 01:56:18,400
- What for?
- Our symbol of good faith.

1389
01:56:19,280 --> 01:56:22,966
Tell Chief 5 Barrels I'd be happy
to join my brave ladies.

1390
01:56:25,240 --> 01:56:29,325
Yes, ma'am. I'll make all
the arrangements for the exchange. Sir.

1391
01:56:29,440 --> 01:56:31,681
Good night, Slater.

1392
01:56:31,800 --> 01:56:33,768
It's scheduled for dawn.

1393
01:56:40,720 --> 01:56:42,370
Oh...

1394
01:56:42,480 --> 01:56:45,211
Thaddeus, isn't it wonderful? 10 wagons.

1395
01:56:45,320 --> 01:56:48,130
That's the exact number
held by the Irish teamsters.

1396
01:56:48,240 --> 01:56:53,007
You're not gonna have to confiscate
any of Mr Wallingham's wagons after all.

1397
01:56:53,760 --> 01:56:55,728
Yes... well...

1398
01:56:55,840 --> 01:56:58,969
It's a long day tomorrow, Cora,
and you need rest.

1399
01:56:59,080 --> 01:57:01,048
I'll take you back to your camp.

1400
01:57:03,920 --> 01:57:06,730
- Oh...
- Oh, I can get back by myself.

1401
01:57:06,840 --> 01:57:10,242
- You're sure?
- Oh, Thaddeus...

1402
01:57:10,360 --> 01:57:14,649
You're so kind and generous... and brave.

1403
01:57:20,560 --> 01:57:22,528
Good night, Thaddeus.

1404
01:57:25,320 --> 01:57:28,961
♪ Stand up, we'll march to Denver

1405
01:57:29,320 --> 01:57:31,926
♪ No more wine or beer...

1406
01:57:42,240 --> 01:57:44,208
♪ We shall save

1407
01:57:45,000 --> 01:57:46,968
♪ We shall save

1408
01:57:47,840 --> 01:57:50,730
♪ We shall save another soul

1409
01:57:51,640 --> 01:57:54,120
- ♪ Hallelujah.
- Frank.

1410
01:57:54,240 --> 01:57:56,288
- Huh?
- Frank, she's all fixed up.

1411
01:57:57,280 --> 01:58:00,682
- What?
- Frank, listen carefully. This is important.

1412
01:58:00,800 --> 01:58:02,962
Frank! Hey, Frank!

1413
01:58:04,920 --> 01:58:06,922
You've been drinkin'.

1414
01:58:07,040 --> 01:58:11,568
Frank, listen carefully. If you could
get your wagon train outta here,

1415
01:58:11,680 --> 01:58:17,323
if you could cross the river so as nobody,
no lnjuns, women or army could follow,

1416
01:58:17,440 --> 01:58:19,920
would you do it?

1417
01:58:20,040 --> 01:58:22,042
- How?
- Wait a minute!

1418
01:58:22,160 --> 01:58:25,130
You'd have to give up
them 10 wagons on the exchange.

1419
01:58:25,240 --> 01:58:28,130
Now, here's what we do.
We take the rest of the wagons

1420
01:58:28,240 --> 01:58:31,847
and we ride across Quicksand Bottoms.
None of them people could see us.

1421
01:58:31,960 --> 01:58:33,928
- Hold it.
- We'd get across the river...

1422
01:58:34,040 --> 01:58:36,964
Hold on! Just a damn minute now.

1423
01:58:37,080 --> 01:58:40,482
Nobody can cross Quicksand Bottoms
cos they'd sink.

1424
01:58:40,600 --> 01:58:43,809
We can. There's a way, Frank.

1425
01:58:43,920 --> 01:58:46,366
I found it five years ago.

1426
01:58:46,480 --> 01:58:50,849
A bunch of scalp-hungry lnjuns
chased me right up to the edge.

1427
01:58:50,960 --> 01:58:54,248
I knew for sure they'd get me
that night if I didn't get across.

1428
01:58:54,360 --> 01:58:58,968
I just pointed my Billy girl south
and let her go. She didn't miss a step.

1429
01:58:59,560 --> 01:59:03,201
I did the same thing tonight.
She took me right across.

1430
01:59:03,600 --> 01:59:09,687
I've staked out a trail across the Bottoms
with my red flannel. We can't miss it.

1431
01:59:09,800 --> 01:59:15,125
We'll take all the wagons you got and go
across, a-pullin' up the stakes as we go.

1432
01:59:15,240 --> 01:59:17,846
They won't even know
what happened to us.

1433
01:59:17,960 --> 01:59:23,126
Once across the Bottoms, it's a straight
shoot to Denver over flat, open country.

1434
01:59:23,240 --> 01:59:26,767
- We'll be free and clear.
- (Wallingham chuckles)

1435
01:59:26,880 --> 01:59:31,090
- Hallelujah! Hallelujah!
- Sh! Hush up!

1436
01:59:31,520 --> 01:59:34,444
Yeah... My sentiments exactly.

1437
01:59:35,480 --> 01:59:37,448
Hallelujah.

1438
01:59:38,760 --> 01:59:40,728
Here's one.

1439
01:59:43,440 --> 01:59:45,408
Here's another one.

1440
01:59:49,600 --> 01:59:51,682
Here...

1441
01:59:51,800 --> 01:59:54,007
and here's one.

1442
01:59:54,120 --> 01:59:56,851
- But what are they?
- I don't know.

1443
01:59:56,960 --> 02:00:00,806
- But does it look familiar?
- It looks like Mr Jones' underwear.

1444
02:00:00,920 --> 02:00:04,208
- It is.
- Are you... are you sure?

1445
02:00:04,320 --> 02:00:08,530
The ladies have confirmed it. He's not
wearing those underdrawers now.

1446
02:00:08,640 --> 02:00:13,851
They're torn to shreds and spread out
on stakes all across Quicksand Bottoms.

1447
02:00:15,160 --> 02:00:18,243
- Where's Group C?
- (whistles)

1448
02:00:21,640 --> 02:00:24,610
Mrs Massingale, have you any idea
what these stakes are for?

1449
02:00:24,720 --> 02:00:27,610
I'm not sure, but I know
what we're gonna do with them.

1450
02:00:27,720 --> 02:00:30,041
- What?
- Move them.

1451
02:01:00,600 --> 02:01:03,604
Stay between those red markers.
Don't be a-laggin' behind.

1452
02:01:03,720 --> 02:01:05,688
Keep your wagons up close, all of ya!

1453
02:01:05,800 --> 02:01:08,770
Militia, when we move out,
get on the wagons.

1454
02:01:11,160 --> 02:01:15,768
That's the signal, sir. All wagons ready for
exchange. Platoons A and B in position.

1455
02:01:15,880 --> 02:01:20,249
Get down there, Buell. Send Mrs
Massingale over to the exchange point.

1456
02:01:24,120 --> 02:01:26,361
- Mrs Massingale!
- Whoa, whoa!

1457
02:01:26,480 --> 02:01:29,802
- Mrs Massingale, excuse me.
- I'm busy right now, Mr O'Flaherty.

1458
02:01:29,920 --> 02:01:32,890
- It's about them 10 wagons.
- What's the matter with them?

1459
02:01:33,000 --> 02:01:36,607
- Nothing, mum, but they ain't whiskey.
- Ain't whiskey?

1460
02:01:36,720 --> 02:01:40,566
No, mum. Those wagons is filled
with French champagne. All of 'em.

1461
02:01:40,680 --> 02:01:43,650
You know anything about
French champagne, mum?

1462
02:01:43,760 --> 02:01:46,969
Well, I sipped some once
on my second honeymoon in Paris.

1463
02:01:47,080 --> 02:01:50,482
Aye, but it was most likely cold.
These bottles ain't, they're warm.

1464
02:01:50,600 --> 02:01:54,924
If you open a bottle of warm champagne,
especially when it's been shooken up,

1465
02:01:55,040 --> 02:01:57,202
well, it's...

1466
02:01:58,280 --> 02:02:02,046
- You mean they explode?
- Like a Marsh gun, about a .58 calibre.

1467
02:02:02,160 --> 02:02:04,925
We gotta handle those bottles
like dynamite.

1468
02:02:05,040 --> 02:02:08,647
That's why they hired us Irish teamsters.
It's our business.

1469
02:02:08,760 --> 02:02:11,570
What's gonna happen when
them savages get them wagons?

1470
02:02:11,680 --> 02:02:13,921
What's gonna happen to that champagne?

1471
02:02:14,040 --> 02:02:16,042
- Explosions?
- Right.

1472
02:02:16,160 --> 02:02:18,162
I just thought someone oughta know.

1473
02:02:18,280 --> 02:02:22,410
- Have you told Colonel Gearhart yet?
- Oh, no, mum. I've been afeard to.

1474
02:02:22,520 --> 02:02:24,488
What's holding you up, Mrs Massingale?

1475
02:02:24,600 --> 02:02:28,321
I'm sorry, Sergeant Buell.
Excuse me, Mr O'Flaherty.

1476
02:02:41,120 --> 02:02:43,248
Mrs Massingale,
we have a bit of a problem.

1477
02:02:43,360 --> 02:02:45,931
Chief 5 Barrels insists on
taking the first wagon,

1478
02:02:46,040 --> 02:02:49,886
and his two brothers-in-law
the second and third wagons,

1479
02:02:50,000 --> 02:02:55,006
and Elks-Runner the fourth wagon. That
leaves nobody in charge on their side.

1480
02:02:55,120 --> 02:02:57,202
Me in charge.

1481
02:02:57,320 --> 02:03:01,370
You? You speak our tongue?

1482
02:03:01,480 --> 02:03:04,848
I speak with straight tongue.
Me in charge good. Drink later.

1483
02:03:04,960 --> 02:03:07,884
We'll agree to your taking charge
on one condition,

1484
02:03:08,000 --> 02:03:10,651
that I stay at the exchange point
the whole time.

1485
02:03:10,760 --> 02:03:13,240
- Me there... whole time.
- Good.

1486
02:03:15,080 --> 02:03:17,242
One moment, please, Captain.

1487
02:03:22,160 --> 02:03:25,528
Mrs Massingale, I'll never forgive
myself for having failed you.

1488
02:03:25,640 --> 02:03:27,881
10 wagonloads of whiskey to the Indians.

1489
02:03:28,000 --> 02:03:31,322
- I've destroyed the crusade.
- Not quite yet.

1490
02:03:31,440 --> 02:03:33,602
- What?
- Give me a hatpin.

1491
02:03:35,320 --> 02:03:37,288
Hatpin?

1492
02:03:37,760 --> 02:03:40,809
Our goal is still in sight, Louise.
Courage, ladies!

1493
02:03:45,960 --> 02:03:48,531
First three ladies, front and centre.

1494
02:03:50,120 --> 02:03:53,283
There they go, sir.
Three women starting across...

1495
02:03:54,480 --> 02:03:56,608
- Sir... sir!
- What's the matter?

1496
02:03:56,720 --> 02:04:00,566
That Massingale woman.
She's heading for the exchange point.

1497
02:04:02,800 --> 02:04:06,088
- Why's that symbol of good faith there?
- I can't say, sir.

1498
02:04:10,760 --> 02:04:14,651
- Roll the first wagon.
- First wagon... roll!

1499
02:04:41,640 --> 02:04:45,008
What's he trying to do,
bolting out of there like that?

1500
02:04:45,880 --> 02:04:50,090
- Roll wagon two.
- Wagon two... roll!

1501
02:04:51,800 --> 02:04:53,768
Ladies, move out!

1502
02:04:55,240 --> 02:04:57,720
Wagon two, roll!

1503
02:04:59,480 --> 02:05:01,767
Next three ladies, front and centre.

1504
02:05:17,760 --> 02:05:19,649
<i>(corks popping)</i>

1505
02:05:19,760 --> 02:05:22,684
Tell 'em not to bolt like that.
Our teams'll get out of control.

1506
02:05:22,800 --> 02:05:24,962
Tell those Indians not to bolt like that.

1507
02:05:37,280 --> 02:05:39,248
<i>(popping)</i>

1508
02:06:07,600 --> 02:06:10,570
- Roll wagon three.
- Wagon three, roll!

1509
02:06:12,720 --> 02:06:15,200
Roll!

1510
02:06:15,640 --> 02:06:17,927
Next three ladies, front and centre!

1511
02:06:21,080 --> 02:06:23,048
Well, move out. Go!

1512
02:06:41,800 --> 02:06:43,609
<i>(popping)</i>

1513
02:06:43,720 --> 02:06:47,805
Don't let those idiots bolt that way.
Roll the wagons slowly!

1514
02:06:48,240 --> 02:06:50,766
No, not those wagons.
Hold those wagons back!

1515
02:06:50,880 --> 02:06:54,601
Hold on to those teams! There's gonna
be a runaway! Hold 'em, I say!

1516
02:06:54,720 --> 02:06:58,691
Whoa! Somebody tell them Indians
not to go bolting out there like that!

1517
02:06:59,240 --> 02:07:02,164
Wagon four, roll!

1518
02:07:04,520 --> 02:07:08,286
Next three ladies, front and centre!
Hold the wagons back!

1519
02:07:19,920 --> 02:07:21,729
Hold those teams back!

1520
02:07:24,240 --> 02:07:26,686
- Hold those wagons!
- Hold those wagons!

1521
02:07:30,000 --> 02:07:31,968
Don't bolt!

1522
02:08:03,920 --> 02:08:05,649
- Hold 'em back!
- Hold 'em back!

1523
02:08:10,560 --> 02:08:13,564
Carter! Cut those teams off
and bring 'em back!

1524
02:08:13,680 --> 02:08:15,444
HQ!

1525
02:08:18,240 --> 02:08:19,844
HQ!

1526
02:08:46,920 --> 02:08:49,605
- Look out! Look out!
- We got a stampede!

1527
02:08:49,720 --> 02:08:51,688
Hold on to that team!

1528
02:08:51,800 --> 02:08:54,041
Don't let 'em follow them other horses!

1529
02:08:54,360 --> 02:08:56,203
No, not that way!

1530
02:08:59,800 --> 02:09:02,007
You're going the wrong way!

1531
02:09:02,120 --> 02:09:05,329
They're gonna stampede!
You'll never get 'em back!

1532
02:09:05,440 --> 02:09:07,408
Full them up! Full them up there!

1533
02:09:08,000 --> 02:09:11,766
Hey, you! Full them up!
You're going the wrong way!

1534
02:09:25,000 --> 02:09:27,162
The whole Wallingham train!

1535
02:10:08,800 --> 02:10:10,768
Hey! Hey, you!

1536
02:10:11,520 --> 02:10:13,488
Tum 'em, tum 'em!

1537
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:18,401
Head 'em back to the quicksands.

1538
02:10:37,680 --> 02:10:39,648
<i>(Mrs Massingale screams)</i>

1539
02:11:17,040 --> 02:11:19,247
Uh... company, halt.

1540
02:11:36,840 --> 02:11:38,808
Whoa! Whoa!

1541
02:11:40,120 --> 02:11:43,090
Get 'em on through there!
Follow them red flags!

1542
02:11:45,800 --> 02:11:48,201
All right! Follow them red flags as you go.

1543
02:11:48,320 --> 02:11:53,008
Stay right along in line with them.
Follow them little red flags there.

1544
02:12:06,720 --> 02:12:08,529
Follow them markers!

1545
02:12:26,640 --> 02:12:30,247
Stay right in line with them.
Follow them little red flags and...

1546
02:12:31,400 --> 02:12:33,846
He)', you! No, not that way!

1547
02:12:40,880 --> 02:12:42,803
Frank! Look out, Frank!

1548
02:12:45,000 --> 02:12:47,401
Whoa! Whoa!

1549
02:12:49,400 --> 02:12:53,086
Rafe, Rafe! Come over here
and give me a hand with this thing!

1550
02:12:55,400 --> 02:12:57,368
Help me "P!

1551
02:13:00,280 --> 02:13:02,248
Get 'em outta here!

1552
02:13:03,200 --> 02:13:05,851
- OK, take 'em out!
- Take 'em outta here.

1553
02:13:06,720 --> 02:13:08,688
Go on, take 'em out!

1554
02:13:15,280 --> 02:13:17,248
<i>Ulelches)</i>

1555
02:13:43,560 --> 02:13:46,370
Tell the colonel
the Indians are firing on us!

1556
02:13:48,040 --> 02:13:50,008
Return fire!

1557
02:16:17,880 --> 02:16:19,769
<i>(whooping)</i>

1558
02:16:19,880 --> 02:16:21,769
<i>(gunfire)</i>

1559
02:16:21,880 --> 02:16:24,451
Don't shoot! Don't shoot!

1560
02:17:06,720 --> 02:17:09,041
Don't shoot!

1561
02:17:21,560 --> 02:17:23,722
I beg your pardon!

1562
02:17:23,840 --> 02:17:25,888
What do you think you're doing to me?

1563
02:17:26,200 --> 02:17:28,487
My God! They've got Mrs Massingale!

1564
02:17:38,320 --> 02:17:40,800
Sir! Sir, they're waving a flag of truce!

1565
02:17:41,920 --> 02:17:44,810
It's a woman's petticoat. Charge!

1566
02:17:55,600 --> 02:17:57,568
- Thaddeus!
- You!

1567
02:18:05,360 --> 02:18:08,091
We go home now.

1568
02:18:08,200 --> 02:18:11,568
- You speak my tongue?
- I speak with straight tongue.

1569
02:18:11,880 --> 02:18:13,848
We go home, hunt buffalo.

1570
02:18:14,880 --> 02:18:17,247
Peaceful Indian. Forget presents.

1571
02:18:18,480 --> 02:18:22,565
You hunt buffalo in peace.
You hunt deer of green forest in peace.

1572
02:18:22,680 --> 02:18:24,921
You go home in peace. But go home!

1573
02:18:33,640 --> 02:18:35,608
Oh...

1574
02:18:36,920 --> 02:18:39,082
Hey. He!!!

1575
02:18:40,000 --> 02:18:42,446
Hey! Hey!

1576
02:18:53,320 --> 02:18:55,288
Get 'em outta there.

1577
02:19:06,320 --> 02:19:09,210
Rafe! Rafe! Throw me that rope!

1578
02:19:09,320 --> 02:19:10,765
Yeah. Get a rope!

1579
02:19:10,880 --> 02:19:14,771
Hold what you got, Frank. I'm a-comin'.
I'll help ya. Hold what you got, Frank!

1580
02:19:14,880 --> 02:19:16,848
I'll be right there with you.

1581
02:19:24,400 --> 02:19:26,368
Make it fast to that tree.

1582
02:19:35,880 --> 02:19:37,882
Get the slack outta that line.

1583
02:19:38,200 --> 02:19:40,168
Tighten up on it.

1584
02:19:41,200 --> 02:19:43,487
Now, hold on that. Hold it! Hold it!

1585
02:20:36,320 --> 02:20:41,326
<i>Companies A and B of the cavalry
escorted the ex-temperance marchers</i>

1586
02:20:41,440 --> 02:20:45,047
<i>back to their husbands and
hungry children at Fort Russell.</i>

1587
02:20:45,520 --> 02:20:47,761
<i>It is to be assumed some time passed</i>

1588
02:20:47,880 --> 02:20:51,930
<i>before the Indians were able to
regain their customary composure.</i>

1589
02:20:52,680 --> 02:20:57,083
<i>But it is known that the exploits
of their journey became tribal legend,</i>

1590
02:20:57,200 --> 02:21:02,127
<i>to be told over and over again,
from generation to generation,</i>

1591
02:21:02,680 --> 02:21:05,001
<i>with slight revisions.</i>

1592
02:21:05,360 --> 02:21:09,206
<i>The Denver Free Militia dissolved,
never to march again.</i>

1593
02:21:09,600 --> 02:21:13,924
<i>And, of course, the strike
of the Irish teamsters failed,</i>

1594
02:21:14,040 --> 02:21:17,522
<i>and the Wallingham Freighting Company
went bankrupt,</i>

1595
02:21:17,960 --> 02:21:20,122
<i>having no visible assets.</i>

1596
02:21:21,240 --> 02:21:24,926
You know, Frank,
some lnjuns told me once...

1597
02:21:25,040 --> 02:21:27,486
Reliable lnjuns, Frank.

1598
02:21:27,600 --> 02:21:31,127
They said a Cheyenne brave
and his pony sunk right here,

1599
02:21:31,240 --> 02:21:33,891
and dured if they didn't ooze up again

1600
02:21:34,000 --> 02:21:37,447
just as natural-lookin'
and as pretty as you please.

1601
02:21:38,400 --> 02:21:40,368
Oh, they was dead, of course,

1602
02:21:40,480 --> 02:21:43,450
but right near the top
where you could grab easy.

1603
02:21:44,960 --> 02:21:47,850
It might be worth waitin' for, eh, Frank?

1604
02:21:48,640 --> 02:21:50,847
Frank?

1605
02:21:50,960 --> 02:21:52,610
<i>(bubbling)</i>

1606
02:21:52,720 --> 02:21:55,121
There. You see?

1607
02:21:59,000 --> 02:22:02,083
<i>So ended the great disaster
at Quicksand Bottoms.</i>

1608
02:22:02,800 --> 02:22:04,768
<i>Oh, yes. Mrs Massingale.</i>

1609
02:22:06,120 --> 02:22:11,251
<i>Cora Templeton Massingale retired from
participation in temperance movements.</i>

1610
02:22:12,200 --> 02:22:14,931
<i>A military wedding
was held at Fort Russell.</i>

1611
02:22:18,600 --> 02:22:22,889
<i>As it fumed out, it was a double wedding.</i>

1612
02:22:26,040 --> 02:22:30,204
<i>A homestead claim was filed
by Mr Jones and Mr Wallingham</i>

1613
02:22:30,320 --> 02:22:34,928
<i>on a piece of land encompassing
the entire Quicksand Bottoms area.</i>

1614
02:22:42,600 --> 02:22:43,647
<i>(bubbling)</i>

1615
02:22:48,720 --> 02:22:51,291
(whispers) Frank? Frank.

1616
02:22:52,200 --> 02:22:53,531
- Frank!
- What?

1617
02:22:53,640 --> 02:22:55,688
- Frank!
- <i>(bubbling)</i>

1618
02:23:11,080 --> 02:23:13,048
Come on. Pull, Frank.

1619
02:23:15,160 --> 02:23:17,128
Careful, careful, careful.

1620
02:23:28,440 --> 02:23:30,408
<i>(both chuckle)</i>

1621
02:23:37,640 --> 02:23:40,041
